article.description: Tim Thomas hit a 3-pointer from the left corner with 9.9 seconds remaining, and the struggling Bucks rallied from a 17-point second-quarter deficit to hand the Dallas Mavericks their second home defeat of the season, 110-107 Monday night.
article.headline: Despite Nowitzki's 40 points, Mavs fall at home
article.linkText: Bucks rally from 17 down to win in Dallas
article.story:
DALLAS (AP) -- The Milwaukee Bucks waited until 2002 was almost over before registering their most significant victory of the season. Tim Thomas hit a 3-pointer from the left corner with 9.9 seconds remaining, and the struggling Bucks rallied from a 17-point second-quarter deficit to hand the Dallas Mavericks their second home defeat of the season, 110-107 Monday night. "It was a great win for us,'' Bucks coach George Karl said. "I think we needed a win like this to give us a boost. We've been talking about winning a big game on the road, and that's what we did.'' Thomas, who entered the game shooting 31 percent from 3-point range, came up with the biggest basket of the game for Milwaukee (13-17). He made his way along the baseline and got free for the decisive jumper. "I was just trying to get open,'' Thomas said. "I started running the baseline, nobody played me, and I was able to hit it.'' Dirk Nowitzki, who matched his career high with 40 points, made two free throws with 2.9 seconds left to cut the deficit to 109-107, but Thomas hit one of two foul shots with 2.6 seconds left. Dallas, which fell to 14-2 at home, seemed ready to take control when Michael Finley hit a baseline jumper with 1:09 remaining for a 105-100 lead. But the Bucks closed with a 10-2 run, including the 3-pointer by Thomas that gave Milwaukee a 107-105 lead. Steve Nash launched a 3-point shot for the Mavericks, but it fell far short of the rim, and Sam Cassell collected the loose ball. Cassell, who led the Bucks with 28 points, was fouled and hit two free throws with 4.5 seconds remaining for a 109-105 advantage. The Bucks had matchup problems against Nowitzki, who went 14-of-16 from the free-throw line and had 14 rebounds. Nowitzki took little comfort from his strong individual performance. "A loss is a loss, and numbers don't mean anything in a loss,'' Nowitzki said. Nash and Finley went a combined 14-for-39 from the field. Nash finished with 17 points and Finley had 16. Dallas, still a league-best 25-5 overall, went 3-for-19 from 3-point range. Thomas scored 17 points, Michael Redd and Jason Caffey had 16 each, and Ray Allen added 15 points for the Bucks, who had lost five of their previous seven. The Mavericks led by as many as 17 in the second quarter, but the Bucks went on a 23-9 run over the final 7:46 of the period to trim the deficit to 53-50 at halftime. "That second quarter, we were allowing Dallas to do whatever they wanted,'' Cassell said. "We just tried to tighten it up, and then made a run and built off of that.'' Mavericks coach Don Nelson was especially critical of the effort by starting power forward Raef LaFrentz, who made only one of five field-goal attempts and finished with two points and three rebounds in 16 minutes. "What performance? He didn't perform tonight,'' Nelson said. "I'm tired of hearing about confidence problems. He is a guy who has had enough opportunities to get his game in order and hasn't. ... There will be no punches pulled anymore. We need him to be an effective player, and he hasn't been. It's really that simple.'' The Bucks showed they could keep up offensively with the Mavericks, the league's highest-scoring team. Milwaukee began the night third in the league in scoring. "We played against a team equally able to score,'' Nelson said. "We got beat at our own game.''

Game notes
Mavericks C Shawn Bradley started but was pulled after 13 seconds because the Bucks opened with a "small ball'' three-guard lineup. Bradley came back to finish with 13 points and eight rebounds. ...Dallas G Walt Williams missed his second consecutive game with a strained left knee. ... Milwaukee had its second road win over a team with a record of better than .500 this season. The Bucks are 5-11 on the road. ... Nowitzki had his 16th double-double of the season. ... Dallas fell to 20-2 when leading after three quarters.
